docs.abstract: The Senate is poised to rebuke President Trump’s national emergency declaration at the southwestern border. The only question: how big the Senate margin will be.
docs.snippet: The Senate is poised to rebuke President Trump’s national emergency declaration at the southwestern border. The only question: how big the Senate margin will be.
docs.lead_paragraph: With Senator Rand Paul’s decision to support a resolution to block President Trump’s emergency declaration, Congress appears ready to deliver a stern rebuke to the president over his border wall and a clear statement that it will defend its ability to control federal spending.

headline.main: Senate Has Votes to Overturn Trump’s Emergency Declaration
headline.print_headline: Senate Is Poised to Reject Border Emergency

docs.abstract: The decision came after a year of failed efforts by the Trump administration to compel India to lower its trade barriers and as the administration tries to ease tensions with China.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump has decided to strip India of a special status that exempts billions of dollars worth of Indian exports from American tariffs, raising new trade tensions with the world’s second most populous country.

headline.print_headline: Trump to Strip India of Special Tariff Status, Escalating Tensions

docs.abstract: At issue in the ruling is the post-World War II practice of keeping governments immune from lawsuits.
docs.snippet: At issue in the ruling is the post-World War II practice of keeping governments immune from lawsuits.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — A court in Luxembourg has ruled against a group of Sept. 11 victims in a novel lawsuit seeking $1.6 billion in Iranian assets, bringing to a head a long growing disagreement about a significant question of international law: Should governments be immune from lawsuits even when they are accused of responsibility for terrorist attacks?

headline.main: European Court Rules Against 9/11 Victims Seeking $1.6 Billion From Iran
headline.print_headline: Iran Wins Court Ruling in 9/11 Lawsuit

docs.abstract: The Iowa Republican’s racist language has attracted scorn and political challengers, but he is aggressively reasserting his presence in his congressional district.
docs.snippet: The Iowa Republican’s racist language has attracted scorn and political challengers, but he is aggressively reasserting his presence in his congressional district.
docs.lead_paragraph: ALGONA, Iowa — For nearly two decades, Representative Steve King pummeled Republican primary challengers, dispatched Democrats, even a former Iowa governor’s wife, and glided to victory in his conservative district. He spent little energy on fund-raising, put few controls on his racist language and made little effort to hold town halls with constituents.

headline.main: Steve King, Facing Backlash From Both Parties, Fights for Political Life
headline.print_headline: Facing Sturdy Backlash, And Fresh Challengers, King Digs In for a Fight

docs.abstract: As President Trump’s aides try to focus on his accomplishments in office and he denounces old enemies, the tension may build between the campaign and Mr. Trump, who trusts his gut above all else.
docs.snippet: As President Trump’s aides try to focus on his accomplishments in office and he denounces old enemies, the tension may build between the campaign and Mr. Trump, who trusts his gut above all else.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — On a former trading floor in an office tower in Rosslyn, Va., with sweeping views of the Potomac River, the Trump 2020 campaign is settling in. It has about 40 staff members and counting, reported $19.2 million in cash on hand in its last report and has spent $4.5 million on online ads since December.

headline.main: Trump’s 2020 Campaign: A Traditional Operation With a Wild-Card Candidate
headline.print_headline: Traditional Campaign, Except for One Thing: Wild-Card Candidate

docs.lead_paragraph: BALTIMORE — In a case that exposed the government’s embarrassing failure to secure its secrets, a 54-year-old former National Security Agency contractor pleaded guilty on Thursday to taking classified documents home in a deal likely to put him in prison for nine years.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump said on Thursday that the federal government would continue to fund the Special Olympics, reversing his administration’s decision to cut the allocated money, which his education secretary, Betsy DeVos, had been defending on Capitol Hill only hours earlier.

docs.abstract: The Committee on Foreign Investment in the United States is forcing a Chinese company to sell its stake in Grindr, a gay dating app, over national security concerns.
docs.snippet: The Committee on Foreign Investment in the United States is forcing a Chinese company to sell its stake in Grindr, a gay dating app, over national security concerns.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration is expanding its efforts to block Chinese acquisitions in the United States, moving to force a Chinese firm that owns Grindr, the gay dating app, to relinquish control over concerns that Beijing could use personal information to blackmail or influence American officials, according to people familiar with the situation.

headline.main: Grindr Is Owned by a Chinese Firm, and the U.S. Is Trying to Force It to Sell
headline.print_headline: U.S. Is Seeking to Force China to Sell Dating App
